  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the US, you generally don't get taxed on charitable donations you make. You might be thinking about deducting those donations from your income to lower your tax burden. Here's a breakdown:\n\n**Deduction Limits:**\n\n*   **General Rule:** You can deduct contributions to qualified charities up to 60% of your Adjusted Gross Income (AGI). AGI is your gross income minus certain deductions (like student loan interest).\n*   **Cash Contributions (Certain Public Charities):** For cash contributions to certain public charities, you can deduct up to 60% of your AGI.\n*   **Contributions of Capital Gain Property:** Contributions of capital gain property (like stocks or real estate held for more than one year) are generally deductible up to 30% of your AGI. There are special rules and potential reductions in the deductible amount depending on the type of property and the charity involved.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n1.  **Itemizing Deductions:** To deduct charitable donations, you need to itemize deductions on Schedule A of Form 1040. This means you forgo the standard deduction. The standard deduction amounts are quite high now, so itemizing only makes sense if your total itemized deductions (including charitable donations, state and local taxes (SALT), medical expenses, etc.) exceed the standard deduction for your filing status.\n2.  **Qualified Charity:** The organization you donate to must be a qualified charity as defined by the IRS. You can check an organization's status using the IRS's Tax Exempt Organization Search tool on IRS.gov.\n3.  **Record Keeping:** Keep good records of your donations.\n    *   For cash donations under \\$250, a bank record, payroll deduction record, or written communication from the charity is usually sufficient.\n    *   For cash donations of \\$250 or more, you need a written acknowledgment from the charity.\n    *   For non-cash donations (like property) over \\$500, you'll need to complete Form 8283.\n    *   For non-cash donations over \\$5,000, you generally need a qualified appraisal.\n4.  **Limits on Certain Types of Property:** There are special rules for donations of property, like clothing or household items. Generally, the items must be in good used condition or better to be deductible.\n5.  **Quid Pro Quo:** If you receive something of benefit in return for your donation (e.g., a dinner, tickets to an event), you can only deduct the amount of your contribution that exceeds the value of the benefit you received.\n6.  **Carryover:** If you donate more than the AGI limits allow in a given year, you can carry forward the excess deduction for up to five years.\n\n**In summary:** You don't get taxed *on* your donations. However, there are limits to how much you can deduct *from* your income based on your AGI. Itemizing, qualified charities, and good record-keeping are essential for taking a charitable deduction.\n\n***\n\n***Disclaimer:** I am an AI Chatbot and not a financial or tax advisor. This information is for general guidance only. Consult with a qualified tax professional for personalized advice.*",
